"Ospina A.F., Mora C.","Effect of body size on reef fish tolerance to extreme low and high temperatures",2004,"Environmental Biology of Fishes","70","4",,"339","343",,,10.1023/B:EBFI.0000035429.39129.34,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-3943052787&partnerID=40&md5=0490a2fd8f880438e439f479b21c7754","Secc. de Biología Marina, Universidad del Valle, A.A. 25360, Cali, Colombia, Colombia; Secc. de Biología Marina, Universidad del Valle, A.A. 25360, Cali, Colombia; Dept. B., Colombia","Ospina, A.F., Secc. de Biología Marina, Universidad del Valle, A.A. 25360, Cali, Colombia, Colombia; Mora, C., Secc. de Biología Marina, Universidad del Valle, A.A. 25360, Cali, Colombia; Dept. B., Colombia","Understanding the thermal physiology of tropical marine organisms has become an issue of major interest due to the potential impact of current global changes in temperature. In this study we report the effect of body size on the thermal tolerance (as critical thermal maximum (CTMax) and minimum (CTMin)) of seven reef fish species from Gorgona Island (tropical eastern Pacific Ocean). Within the studied species we found little variation in CTMax and CTMin among fishes ranging from juveniles to adults. This suggests that thermal tolerance of small tropical reef fishes is not significantly affected by differences in body size. The reduced intra-specific variation in thermal tolerance found in these species also suggests a limited capability to adapt to extreme thermal conditions and raises concerns regarding current global changes in temperature.","global warming; Pacific Ocean; temperature; thermal tolerance","body size; coral reef; global warming; ichthyofauna; temperature tolerance; Colombia; Gorgona Island; South America; Valle del Cauca; Anthozoa; Pisces",,,,,,"Barrionuevo, W.R., Fernandes, M.N., Critical thermal maxima and minima for curimbata, Prochilodus scrofa Steindachneri, of two different sizes (1995) Aquacul. Res., 26, pp. 447-450; Becker, D., Genoway, R., Evaluation of the critical thermal maximum for determining thermal tolerance of freshwater fish (1979) Environ. Biol. Fish., 4, pp. 245-256; Bennett, W.A., Judd, F.W., Comparison of methods for determining low temperature tolerance: Experiments with Pinfish, Lagodon rhomboides (1992) Copeia, 1992, pp. 1059-1065; Bennett, W., Currier, R.J., Beitinger, T.L., Cold tolerance and potential overwinter of red-bellied piranha, Pygocentrus nattereri, in the United States (1997) Trans. Amer. Fish. Soc., 126, pp. 841-849; Cox, D.K., Effects of three heating rates on the critical thermal maximum of bluegill (1974) Thermal Ecology, pp. 158-163. , J.W. Gibbons & R.R. Sharitz (ed.) U.S. Atomic Energy Commission, Savannah, Georgia; Forchhammer, M.C., Pots, E., Kozlov, M.V., Hughes, L., Climatic signatures in ecology (2000) Trends Ecol. Evol., 15, pp. 286-287; Glynn, P.W., Von Prahl, F.H., Guhl, F., Coral reefs of Gorgona Island, Colombia, with special reference to coral-livores and their influence on community structure and reef development (1982) Anales del Instituto de Investigaciones Marinas Punta de Betin, 12, pp. 185-214; Hughes, L., Biological consequences of global warming: Is the signal already apparent? (2000) Trends Ecol. Evol., 15, pp. 56-61; Hutchison, V., Factors influencing thermal tolerance of individual organisms (1976) Symposium Series of the National Technical Information Service, pp. 10-26. , G.W. Esch & R. McFarlane (ed.) Springfield, VA; Mora, C., Ospina, A.F., Thermal tolerance and potential impact of sea warming on reef fishes from Gorgona Island (Eastern Pacific ocean) (2001) Mar. Biol., 139, pp. 765-769; Mora, C., Ospina, A.F., Experimental effects of la Niña cold temperatures on the survival of reef fishes from Gorgona Island (Tropical Eastern Pacific) (2002) Mar. Biol., 141, pp. 789-793","Secc. de Biología Marina, Universidad del Valle, A.A. 25360, Cali, ColombiaColombia; email: moracamilo@hotmail.com",,,,,,,,03781909,,EBFID,,"English","Environ. Biol. Fishe